{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01WSwx4UA3SPu8f3tEn4XcSX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to generate 10 realistic fake OCR recipe text files with specific requirements:\n\n1. Save to `tools/title-loop/input/{RECIPE_TITLE}.generated.24.txt`\n2. Filename rules:\n   - Use SPACES, not hyphens/underscores\n   - Preserve Polish diacritics\n   - Must match the main title in content (case-insensitive OK)\n\n3. Recipe mix: ~60% English, ~40% Polish, variety of categories\n4. Mix of multi-word and single-word titles\n\n5. Must be DIFFERENT from the long exclusion list provided\n\n6. Pattern requirements:\n   - 5 files with SIMPLE: basic OCR noise (stray numbers, page headers, broken words)\n   - 3 files with OCR_CORRUPTION: misrecognized characters, digit for letter, dotless i, hyphenation artifacts, garbage tokens\n   - 2 files with NARRATIVE: 3-7 lines of prose intro before ingredient list\n\n7. File length: 15-60 lines, spillover files should be 40-60 lines\n\nLet me first come up with 10 unique recipe titles that aren't in the exclusion list:\n\nEnglish recipes (6):\n1. Roasted Garlic Broccoli (simple)\n2. Chocolate Chip Cookies (simple)\n3. Berry Tart (narrative)\n4. Grilled Portobello Mushrooms (ocr_corruption)\n5. Creamy Mushroom Pasta (ocr_corruption)\n6. Herb Crusted Salmon (simple)\n\nPolish recipes (4):\n1. Mak Tarta (simple)\n2. Bigos z Grzybami (ocr_corruption)\n3. Kluski Owocowe (narrative)\n4. Kopytka z Cebulą (simple)\n\nWait, let me check the exclusion list more carefully... I see:\n\n\n- Roasted Garlic Broccoli - NO, it's there! \"Roasted Garlic Broccoli\"\n- Chocolate Chip Cookies - NO, it's there! \"Chocolate Chip Cookies\"\n- Berry Tart - NO, it's there! \"Berry Tart\"\n- Grilled Portobello Mushrooms - NO, it's there! \"Grilled Portobello Mushrooms\"\n\nI need to replace these with titles that aren't already in the exclusion list. Let me go with Herb Roasted Vegetables, Lemon Thyme Chicken, and other options that don't appear in the provided list.\n\nFor English, I'm selecting: Herb Roasted Vegetables (simple), Lemon Thyme Chicken (simple), Caramelized Apple Tart (narrative), Garlic Mushroom Pasta (ocr_corruption), Crispy Potato Cakes (ocr_corruption), and Baked White Fish (simple). For Polish, I'm choosing: Żurek z Kapustą (simple), Kluski z Mąką Żytni (ocr_corruption), Ciasto Malinowe (narrative), and Pierniki Imbirowe (simple). I should double-check these more carefully to ensure none overlap with existing entries. Butter Pasta (simple) - new\n2. Roasted Fennel and Onions (simple) - new\n3. Strawberry Shortcake Story (narrative) - new\n4. Garlic Herb Shrimp (ocr_corruption) - new\n5. Spiced Apple Compote (ocr_corruption) - new\n6. Baked Pear with Honey (simple) - new\n\nPolish (4):\n1. Żurek z Pieczywem (simple) - new\n2. Oscypek z Cebulą (ocr_corruption) - new (Oscypek is in list but not with cebulą)\n3. Sernik Truskawkowy (narrative) - new\n4. Kopytka Pszenne (simple) - new\n\nVerifying these selections against what's already there to make sure they're genuinely distinct additions.\n\nNow organizing the 10 new files by category: 5 simple recipes, 3 with OCR corruption issues, and 2 narrative pieces. The simple category includes Sage Butter Pasta, Roasted Fennel and Onions, Baked Pear with Honey, plus the two Polish entries Żurek z Pieczywem and Kopytka Pszenne. For OCR corruption, I have Garlic Herb Shrimp, Spiced Apple Compote, and Oscypek z Cebulą. The narrative selections are Strawberry Shortcake Story and Sernik Truskawkowy.\n\nEach file will follow its pattern: simple ones get basic noise like stray numbers and broken words, corrupted versions include character misrecognitions and hyphenation artifacts, and narrative files start with 3-7 lines of cooking prose before the ingredient list. Roasted Fennel and Onions\n\nThree fennel bulbs cut into wedges and four large yellow onions quartered get tossed with olive oil, fennel seeds, and dried thyme. I'll roast everything at 200°C for 40-45 minutes, stirring halfway through, then finish with balsamic vinegar, sea salt, and cracked black pepper.\n\nThe dish works well as a warm side alongside roasted chicken or fish, and any leftovers keep in an airtight container for three days. Serves six with fifteen minutes prep and forty-five minutes cooking time.\n\nStrawberry Shortcake Story\n\nThere's something deeply nostalgic about strawberries arriving in spring. My grandmother would reserve the first ripe berries from her garden for this dessert—a way to mark the season's turning and celebrate fresh cream. The recipe has traveled through generations of our family, and preparing it now connects me to those earlier times. butter until the mixture resembles coarse crumbs. Stir in the cream and vanilla until the dough just comes together, then drop spoonfuls onto a baking sheet and bake for 12-15 minutes until golden. While that bakes, toss the sliced strawberries with sugar and let them macerate for 15 minutes to release their juices. Whip the heavy cream with powdered sugar and vanilla until soft peaks form, then layer everything together—shortcake base, berries with their syrup, and a generous dollop of whipped cream. This makes enough for 8 servings.\n\nFor the garlic herb shrimp, I need to heat olive oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat, then add the minced garlic and cook it for about 45 seconds until fragrant—being careful not to let it burn since garlic turns bitter quickly. Once the garlic is ready, add the shrimp and cook them for 2-3 minutes per side.\n\nOnce the shrimp are pink and cooked through, sprinkle the red pepper flakes and fresh herbs over them. Deglaze the pan with lemon juice while stirring, then toss in the basil and parsley just before serving. Finish by seasoning everything to taste with salt and pepper. The dish comes together in about 15 minutes and serves 4—plate it over rice, pasta, or with crusty bread, then top with lemon wedges and extra herbs.\n\nFor the baked pears, I need to preheat the oven to 180°C and arrange the halved, cored pears cut-side up in a baking dish. A mixture of honey, water, cinnamon, cloves, star anise, and vanilla gets gently heated until fragrant, then poured over the pears. The pears are sprinkled with brown sugar and sliced almonds before baking.\n\nThe pears bake for 35-40 minutes until they're tender and golden, then cool slightly before serving. They pair well with vanilla ice cream, whipped cream, or almond biscotti, and will keep refrigerated for up to five days. Each serving provides vitamin C and fiber, with the recipe yielding eight portions in about 50 minutes total time.\n\nFor the spiced apple compote, I'm combining diced apples with caster sugar and water in a saucepan over medium heat, stirring gently until they begin breaking down after 5-7 minutes. Then I'll add cinnamon stick, whole cloves, nutmeg, salt, lemon juice, and vanilla extract to build the warm spice profile.\n\nOnce the apples have fully softened after 15-20 minutes of occasional stirring, I'll remove the pan from heat and take out the whole spices. I can leave it chunky or blend it partially for a smoother consistency. The finished compote keeps refrigerated in sterilized jars for two weeks or can be frozen for longer storage. This makes 12 servings and takes about 35 minutes total.\n\nFor the żurek, I'm starting with the base of sour rye flour broth and building from there. The kielbasa gets sliced, potatoes are cubed, and aromatics like onion and garlic are prepared. I'll heat oil in a large pot and begin sautéing the onion and garlic to develop flavor.\n\nOnce those are softened, I pour in the żur and bring it to a boil. The potatoes go in next and simmer for about 15 minutes until they start to soften. Then the sliced kielbasa is added for another 10 minutes of cooking. I season with salt and pepper to taste, then serve it in bowls with thick slices of rye bread on the side. The whole dish comes together in about 40 minutes and makes 4 servings.\n\nFor the kopytka, I'm combining wheat flour with salt in a large bowl, then creating a well in the center where I add eggs and warm milk. The dough needs about 5-7 minutes of kneading until it becomes smooth and elastic, then I season it with nutmeg. I'll bring salted water to a boil and drop spoonfuls of the dough in—they're done when they float to the surface. uskawkami jest ulubienicą mojej matki, która każdego lata czeka na sezon owoców leśnych. Wspominam, jak siedziałam przy kuchni, obserwując, jak przekładała gęste warstwy sera twarogowego z owocami, umiejętnie budując każdy kawałek tej wyjątkowej potrawy. Ten sernik łączy tradycyjną polską czystość smaku z naturalną słodyczą truskawek - prosty, ale niezapomniany.\n\nSernik to dla mnie symbol rodzinnych spotkań - wspomnienie matki budującej warstwami twaróg z owocami, łącząc tradycję z naturalną słodyczą. Składniki na spód to zmielone ciastka maślane z roztopionym masłem i cukrem, a nadzienie wymaga kilogramowego twarogu chudego.\n\nPrzygotowanie wymaga rozpuszczenia żelatyny w wodzie i delikatnego wymieszania z masą sernikową, a następnie rozłożenia warstw z plasterkowanymi truskawkami. Proces obejmuje również ubijanie twarogu z jajami i ekstraktem waniliowym, a całość wymaga schłodzenia spodu przed dodaniem nadzienia. ide każdy bok przez 2-3 minuty, aż się zarumieni. Oscypek powinien być miękki w środku, ale z chrupiącą skórką. Przełóż na talerz i odłóż na bok.\n\n2. Na tej samej patelni rozgrzej olej i dodaj cebulę. Smaż przez 5-7 minut, aż będzie miękka i lekko przezroczysta, czasem mieszając.\n\n3. Dodaj ocet jabłkowy, miód, czosnek, sól i pieprz. Gotuj jeszcze 2 minuty, aby smaki się połączyły.\n\n4. Ułóż oscypek na talerzu, polej gorącą cebulą i udekoruj świeżą pietruszką. Podawaj natychmiast, gdy ser jest jeszcze ciepły. Dopraw solą, pieprzem i cydrem. Ułóż oscypek na talerzu i polej caramelizowaną cebulą. Podawaj natychmiast jako danie główne lub na chlebie żytnim, na 4 porcje przygotowywane przez 45 minut.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":21183,"cache_read_input_tokens":84762,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":21183},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"aa929ee3-74d9-4b58-8829-9858a8ab6a20","uuid":"9433b7c7-2033-4c87-8d39-826763eaaea7"}
